You could take an object as return value in the `switch` statement. If no string is found, return an object with empty strings.

This approach uses the returned array from [`Array#map`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/map).

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;
&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;
    var query = &quot;Sunday,Monday,Tuesday&quot;,
        days = query.split(&quot;,&quot;).map(p =&gt; {
            var day = { day: &quot;&quot;, value: &quot;&quot; };
            switch (p) {
                case &quot;Sunday&quot;: return { day: &quot;Sunday&quot;, value: &quot;Sun&quot; };
                case &quot;Monday&quot;: return { day: &quot;Monday&quot;, value: &quot;Mon&quot; };
                case &quot;Tuesday&quot;: return { day: &quot;Tuesday&quot;, value: &quot;Tues&quot; };
            }
            return { day: &quot;&quot;, value: &quot;&quot; };
        });

    console.log(days);
&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;
    .as-console-wrapper { max-height: 100% !important; top: 0; }
&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

The current code keeps pushing one object reference on to the result array; defining `day` inside the `map` callback would fix the problem, but causing [side effects](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Side_effect_(computer_science)) isn&#39;t the intent of `map`.

[`Array#map`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Map) accepts a callback parameter which should return the transformed value for each element. The return of `map` itself is the new mutated result array. The callback should not push onto an external array. 

Using a `switch` statement is verbose and difficult to maintain, resulting in a lot of repeated code.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const query = &quot;Sunday,Monday,Tuesday&quot;;
    const days = query.split(&quot;,&quot;).map(e =&gt; {
      return {day: e, value: e.substr(0, 3)};
    });

    console.log(days);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

I noticed you wanted `&quot;Tues&quot;` to be a 4-character abbreviation while `&quot;Sun&quot;` and `&quot;Mon&quot;` are three. I&#39;d recommend a separate object to store these transformations if this is indeed the desired result:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const query = &quot;Sunday,Monday,Tuesday&quot;;
    const abbreviations = {Tuesday: &quot;Tues&quot;};
    const days = query.split(&quot;,&quot;).map(e =&gt; {
      return {day: e, value: abbreviations[e] || e.substring(0, 3)};
    });

    console.log(days);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Essentially, this checks if we have a special abbreviation specified, else just fall back on the first three characters.

